## High-level protocol (roles & flow)

Worker — runs the full simulation, produces artifacts (checkpoints, logs, metrics), creates Merkle root, signs submission.

Witness nodes — at least 3 distinct devices; each independently verifies a randomized sample of artifacts + telemetry consistency and issues a signed attestation (accept/reject).

Coordinator/Smart Contract — collects attestations; if min_validators=3 accept, registers success and issues reward. If conflicting attestations, triggers dispute resolution (replay by neutral validators or full re-run).

Auditor nodes — optionally run full replay for sporadic audit.



---

## Anti-gaming primitives (short)

1. Stake & Slash: validators must stake tokens; bad attestations result in slashing.


2. Device Identity & TPM: validator devices provisioned with unique identity (DID) + hardware root-of-trust (TPM/TEE) for secure key storage.


3. Geo-proof: signed GNSS fix with time-window and proof-of-possession.


4. Sensor diversity: require different sensor classes across 3 nodes (e.g., IMU + camera + magnetometer OR different vantage points).


5. Randomized checkpoint challenge: validators request random Merkle-path proofs for random checkpoint indices derived from unpredictable seed (blockchain block/hash + job_id).


6. Time-locked attestations: require validators to attest within a short, bounded window to make collusion harder.


7. Cross-correlation of telemetry (time-series) between worker and validators.


8. Challenge-response: validators issue small dynamic tests (e.g., ask worker to run N deterministic extra steps and return hash) — worker must respond in allowed timeframe.


9. Reputation & weighting: validator votes weighted by reputation; new validators have low weight until they build history.


10. Quorum diversity enforcement: require the 3 witnesses to be in different network / AS / country / failure domains.




