## Sybil/Collusion resistance

Stake requirement: non-trivial stake to be validator; stake slashed if validator signs false attestations proven later.

Quorum diversity rules: require different ASNs/countries/fault-domains; limit same org validators by policy.

Random selection: validators chosen pseudo-randomly using unpredictable chain seed — prevents worker from pre-arranging validators.

Anti-capture: require majority of validators be hardware-attested devices (not just containers).

Disincentivize collusion: reward split depends on independent validator confirmations; coins for validators locked for a challenge window.



---

## Reputation scoring & economics

Reputation score R per validator updated after each attestation:

R_new = α * R_old + (1-α) * reward_or_penalty where reward_or_penalty ∈ {+1 (correct accept), -k (false accept), -m (false reject)}.


Weight validator votes proportional to log(1+R), but require min_validators regardless of weight.

Slashing logic:

If later full re-run proves a validator attested incorrectly → slash portion of stake, reduce R substantially.

If validator fails to respond to challenges repeatedly → temporary suspension.




---

## Dispute resolution

If conflicting attestations, escalate:

1. Add N additional neutral validators (randomly selected).


2. Optionally perform full replay by high-reputation auditor nodes (on-request, paid by disputing party).


3. Use judicial windows where human auditor intervenes as final arbiter (for high-stakes jobs).




All steps produce signed evidence and audit logs.


---

## Privacy & data minimization

Validators should not request full raw telemetry by default. Use hashed fingerprints and only reveal raw windows when strictly necessary.

Support encrypted artifact storage; validators are given temporary access tokens to fetch only sample blobs.



